Decided to try one of their lunch combos for the first time. I got the Moo Tod combo and it was delicious. The Thai iced tea is a bonus. I’m going to check out their other menu items the next time I come here for dine in or take out. Great job, Sticky Rice.

I got the mango chicken and panang curry through door dash. The mango chicken was absolutely inedible. Mango chicken is supposed to be like orange chicken, just with a mango twist. This dish literally consisted of about 2.5oz of boiled chicken and the rest is about a pound of mango chunks, bell peppers, and pineapple in a watery sauce. I took one bite of the mango and it tasted like warm mango boiled in chicken juice. Absolutely disgusting. The panang curry didn’t have any vegetables the chicken was rubbery and over cooked and the curry sauce was watery and bland. I want to return the mango dish because it’s so disgusting. I can’t believe people are allowed to serve food like this. We are never eating here again.

Ordered delivery from here on 1/3. From the moment we opened the bag, everything was wrong. They did not include one of our entrees in the order EVEN after calling to say they were swapping it with something else because they were out. Two of our appetizers, the chive dumplings and the fried bananas, were inedible. The chive dumplings were burnt on the outside and completely raw on the inside, indicative of grease that is way too hot. The fried bananas came in an open container (our brown bag was sealed so it had to have been left opened at the restaurant). They were also very greasy, hard, and chewy. We will never eat here again after this bad first impression. If I could give them zero stars, I would.
Wonderful to be back after a prolonged absence.   Food is fantastic.   Had to order moo ping and sticky rice!  The long drive was worth it.

Great flavor in the dishes but I was very disappointed at how small the portions have become & this last time when we ordered the Kua Kae (or whatever was the equivalent to that on their take out menu) the eggplant, baby corn, etc. were left out. We had another dish that was supposed to contain mushrooms. Those were non existent. Another dish with jalapeno in it & they gave us one tiny slice for the entire thing. It was a joke. They were very cheap with us & majority of what we ordered had at least one thing missing from their description on the menu. Still great quality food & flavors but for the above reason, I wouldn't go back.

Sticky Rice is our go to carry out thai restaurant. We've always had our orders completed way ahead of schedule, and the food is fantastic. My go to is the pad see ew. The portions are solid, and there's a good amount of veggies and protein they pack in the dish. You don't just get full off of the noodles and sauce (which are so good, that that wouldn't even be a bad thing.) Give this place a try. You won't be disappointed.

This restaurant is the one I always prefer. I go to a lot of restaurants but here I  constantly return again and again. The team is very receptive and the cuisine they serve is so delicious. I am always happy to have a decent meal here. I recommend this place with pleasure.

Please note I am a pescatarian so the smell of fish and seafood does not offend me. I have also traveled through Thailand and China where I ate street food and from authentic restaurants. Perhaps this place was still too authentic for me? Not for the faint at heart.

Wow. Where do I begin? I ordered a few things to eat from here on uber eats, it seemed to have good reviews and I LOVE thai food. But wow. My experience was bad. I ordered the chicken with mango and rice entree, pork fried rice, and fried banana rice paper rolls. The chicken was presented nicely, inside the scooped out mango skin. But the taste of the chicken was so bland. It was literally boiled chicken. The mango and sauce were so cloyingly sweet, the dish was syrupy. I was not prepared for the amount of sweetness. I expected a combination of sweet and savory, not liquid sugar. The worst offender however was the fried rice. The stench!!! It reeked so badly of dead fish/corpse/idk what. My toddler started gagging and ran out of the room. I decided to try it anyway. Nope. Tastes as bad as it smells. Seriously insulting. The only thing that was edible were the fried plantain rolls. I guess one star for those and another for on time delivery. Seriously, pass on this place.

Amazing food, and beautiful presentation. The menu is insanely huge. I will have to go back a hundred times to try everything!
My wife and i ate here for dinner and we both thought it was delicious. Nice authentic Northern Thai. We'll be back.

The food here is delicious! The staff is friendly, but at least a few aren't native English speakers, so be prepared for a small language barrier. BF and I split a couple apps and Thai Northern dishes. The sour bamboo shoots are a unique taste that I really dug. We'll definitely be back. BYOB!

I went there because I thought they closed at 11 like they have it on the website but I get there at 9:40 they tell me they close at 10 it's the winter hours!! It's spring!! I understand it snowed but come on. They did not even offer to take my order as carry out. I was very disappointed. Lost a customer just for that.

I went there with two kids, 5 pm, left there 29$ (27$ bill plus 2$ tips). We came out hungry. Wonton soup was ok, sweet and sour soup was ok. Dumplings were deep fried, overly oily and uncooked inside. The place didn't feel happy. The napkins, utensils, everything was cheap, but the prices were not. Parking wasn't easy - if you are coming from the south, the only way to park is U-turn. Don't try to get into side streets - it is a maze that would take you over 10 min to get out. We went here because of good reviews and the price wise it was said to be a great deal for the money. That is what set wrong expectations. I ate Thai in California and Maryland - the places were modern but this place feels old and unpopular. I guess it is the wrong area to look for modern happy restaurant.
Great BYOB Thai restaurant! Kind of a no frills place but the food more than makes up for it. I highly recommend the Pad Wu Sen
Good thai food with a huge menu!  Not a fan of the plum sauce on the spring rolls, but I have enjoyed all of the entrees I have had including the spicy basil rice, pad see ewe, and the nam prik nhum.

Probably the best Thai I've had in Chicago, and I've been to Thailand. This is northern style thai, and you MUST order the green curry. We had it w/ duck and were very happy w/ our choice. Every dish we ordered was delicious and had a very natural flavor to it.
Nice and Cozy, love the food always great.. bring ur own drinks is even better :) can't get enough of this place

I had high hopes because people rave about this place when talking about Thai food in Chicago. I wasn't thrilled with my chicken Pad see ew to go. I'd give it another shot dining in, and I'd get a curry instead, I think, or maybe just something a bit more interesting (I don't know if I saw drunken noodles on my phone version of the menu, and I guess pad thai is a good metric, if boring). The noodles I got were soggy and I felt pretty shortchanged on the quantity and quality of the chicken. The flavor was average. On the the upside I called ahead and the food was ready in about fifteen minutes as promised, and the staff was friendly when I picked it up.

Place is great. I went with two other people, we ordered two appetizers, 3 entrées and our bill was $48. The waitress was very accommodating to one person in my party who has several food allergies and to myself who wanted to try something authentic. The crowd was mixed, I was pretty dressed up because it was my birthday, but most people were casual. The recommendations were great and the staff was attentive. There was nothing special about our appetizers of crab Rangoon and thai spring rolls, but they made up for it with the entrees.

Menu runs the gamut... includes the typical pad see ewe, some very unique northern thai dishes (not a fan of the thai sausages), and some really adventurous things like the fried worms, which I unfortunately did not get to try. If you are looking for really unique Thai dishes then this is the place for you. It's also BYO.

The most authentic Thai cuisine I have tasted in Chicago can be found right here. The menu here is pretty extensive and making decisions can take a while. Everything sounds awesome and looking around at what others have ordered, everything …
Skip this place. We ordered Sticky rice and it came with a roach. The manager explained it was the exterminators fault....Like that would make our party feel better. This was just plain gross!

Food was great, but there was a really weird smell in the restaurant.  No, I'm not just an ignorant American who doesn't eat ethnic food--I've eaten at a lot of thai places--there was just something weird with the smell and it made me feel a bit grossed out.  I think if I order again I'll get take-out.  There food was really excellent, and I can tell you that it's the best Northern Thai that I've had in a long time.  I got the Pad See Ew, and it was cooked to perfection.  I'm going to order again soon because I really want to give them four stars.  Just that smell in the restaurant was a bit overwhelming.

Had some lunch with my husband here on a rainy day.  We had the sausage, which was actually my favorite part of the meal, as an appetizer.  The flavor was pungent and had flavors that blended well together.  I had the Kow Soy which is a Northern Thai dish which is made of a spicy curry and egg noodles.  It is very difficult to make this dish as I have yet to find somewhere that makes it like they do in Northern Thailand.  It was not the right taste, but it was okay.  Also, don't get the thai tea. The flavor is watered down, and it's too sweet.

AMAZINGGGG THAI FOOD!! The next morning i was craving for their food again.  Its byob and wait time isnt bad, but most importantly its great thai food! the curry served in the pineapple was to die for! LOVE IT LOVE IT LOVE IT!

love the food here. afforadble and tasty. staff is awesome and really great with giving recommendations. they have outdoor seating, ample parking on the street, and really great ambiance. i love the thai basil beef!! must have!!!
Great food and great prices

Sticky Rice is sticky.  In a good way, because it was good and I plan to be back.  Actually, I don't know why I've never even been there before after being from Chicago and having been to so many Thai places in the city.  The service was good and it wasn't even crazy crowded on this Friday night.  I guess since it's kind of outside the downtown area and Lincoln Park and those types of neighborhoods it was fine.  It wasn't dead either - it was just right.  One thing I'd say could have been better was that the entrees were served almost immediately after the appetizers; there needed to be more of a gap.  Everyone was still having the soup when the main entrees arrived.  So we had a BUNCH of food here; much more than was necessary.  So the veggie dumplings were great.  They were small little things, when compared to the normal sized gyoza that I've had at other places.  Very crispy too, because they were deep fried instead of lightly fried.  Definitely yummy though.  Then we had some Tom Kha soup.  Again, it was good.  Then the best thing I had was the Pad Ke Mow.  Really amazing.  One of the best I've had.  I think I'd get it more spicy, the next time I order it.  Then, the red curry was good.  Usually this is my test of how much I like a new Thai place.  In that sense, the red curry was good.  Not that I can pin down what made it less than great.  It was good.  Lastly, we felt a bit too brave and had decided to push our luck and we ended up ordering some Pad something eggplant item.  This was just kind of... meh...  The only disappointing part of the SR.  Oh yeah, I also had a Thai Iced Coffee, which was good.  I look forward to visiting Sticky Rice again.  Add one more good Thai place to my list!

Authentic northern thai food.  They even added outdoor seating.  Service is usually good. Food is good but nothing spectacular.  With every dish you order, they will ask you the level of spicyness you want.  Be careful if you ask for spicy because they will follow your order and make it SPICY, not kidding.  I love that all of their fried rice dishes come with a fried egg...just the way I like it.  They also don't skimp out on the meat.  I order the duck fried rice and I was not able to finish all the meat because there was just way too much.  The panang curry is also very good.  It's just the right consistency, not too think or liquidy. You'd be surprised how many places don't make their curries correctly.  PS. There is plenty of side street parking available.
The thai food here is always good and never disapoints. Perfect for take out but also nice for sitting-in. I would recmmend the tom kha soup and sticky rice.

Small neighborhood cafe that has great food. Service isn't all that great but enough I guess. I would go back there for the food and price but that's all. Parking is street parking and not as easy though.
Thai food
Delicious Thai food.  Went here after a friend returned from Thailand and was able to get her favorites.  I will definitely return here again, the staff if really friendly and the food was great.
The most authentic Thai food in Chicago. I am really picky about my Thai food and this is the only place that does it well!

The "storefront" is very unassuming as a small yellow awning is about all you really see. But once you enter, the smell tells you everything you need to know. The staff was very courteous and took care of me and my sister. But by far the best part about Stick Rice is their food.  You talk about authentic Thai... they have fried caterpillars on the menu. But they have plenty of great options for those less adventurous eaters as well. Start with an appetizer and the soups. I then had a dish I couldn't pronounce that included pineapple & shrimp.  It was FANTASTIC. It was served inside a hollowed out pineapple and had an amazing mix of just enough spice and sweetness. Overall, highly recommended. Oh, and it's BYOB. TIP: Order the spice a notch down from what you normally would at a Thai restaurant.

Cute family owned Thai restaurant and BYOB! Love the spicy beef and sumtum papaya (without shrimp for salads. Great curries and noodle dishes especially pad see ew with beef and chicken pad Thai & Mango chicken. We always leave full and happy. So cheap we usually order 3-4 dishes for sharing and leftovers.

Well I must say that this place has good worms!  I tried the fried caterpillars and they were good!  I feel like Andrew Zimmern from Bizarre Foods.  My buddy and I ordered the Tom Kha Soup with Chicken with a side of sticky rice and fried caterpillars.  The caterpillars added nice crunchy texture to the soup.  Yet I was a bit disappointed when I received the check - $5.50 for worms.  Well it was a good experience nonetheless.  I ordered the Gang Tae Po which is water spinach and pork cooked in thai curry and tamarind paste.  It was spicy and delicious.  My buddy ordered the Cashew Chicken - also good.  The Thai iced tea is so-so.  I tasted/made better.  I will come here again to lure my friends to try fried worms!
Not all that. Yes this joint is full of racism. Unless you're white or yuppies. I'm Thai myself they forgot my fish. How do you forget the fish?
Good Thai food

Let me just say this place is not what it was a couple years ago. I ordered delivery with a crispy pork dish and it had hair still on the bits of crispy pork which I did't get at first, I thought it was some sort of whatever. But then I started picking through the food and found that it was crispy hair on the pork and I almost puked. The other 3 dishes we had were good but I'm probably not going to order from there again.

Great bargain and friendly family atmosphere at sticky rice. The staff was quick to engage us both before they learned of our upcoming trio TI Thailand but of course afterwards. The curries are delicious, pad Thai not to be missed and Thai iced coffee is delicious. Its another BYOB treat that will leave you happy w/ what you ate & what you paid.
